  "duration": 210.59268608000002,
  "text": " Right now, we have folks all throughout Baptist since the summer of 2015, that they are learning how to experiment their way forward. They're learning how to improve patient care, every element of patient care, by experimenting their way forward. You can see our friend Beth up there in the top corner where she is doing some master coaching. And we are very indebted to Beth. She has taught us so much and me personally, but we have seen tremendous impact. We've seen things like infection rates in certain hospitals cut by 68%. We've seen throughput in an OR improved by 75%. We saw one area where the folks reduced the denials by a million dollars. And I could keep on going on, But the important thing to remember what I'm saying was this was not Skip and his team that did this. This was the real people on the front lines learning how to think creatively, think scientifically to experiment their way forward. So you can see that the four step improvement kata, we've baptized it. Mike Rother always likes to tease me about he's never had anything baptized before. And I said, well, you have now. And so there's our four-step improvement, Tata. There on the far right is our logo. That probably didn't mean much to you, but what looks like a triangle represents we're a non-for-profit health care system in Tennessee, Mississippi, and Arkansas. And that represents the threefold ministry of Christ. And the rectangle represents our system. And I just put the word vision. Now each step frames the next step So once we understand what our challenge is what we trying to accomplish normally for us 52 weeks into the future then that going to frame the next step of where are we at today What's the current condition? Once we understand that, we then move to the next target condition. Magic word, there's the word next, because it implies there will be multiple target conditions on our way to the challenge. Target condition is typically two to three weeks into the future. And then we have obstacles, obstacles that are separating us from what we want to do in the target condition. And then we PDSA through that process. Or as my friend Beth likes to say, it's a meta routine. It's a routine that stays the same regardless of the circumstances. It's a routine way of acting and thinking. There's a strong emphasis in everything we do at the Baptist Management System with infusing this kata thinking, this pattern of thought, and even infusing this element of PDSA. Even in conversations at Baptist, you'll hear people say, well, this is what we're going to do. That's the plan. The next part is I'll say, well, what do you expect to happen as a result of doing that? Right. So that's part of that plan session. Then we're going to do something. Then we find out what really happened. Many times it's different than what we thought was going to happen. And then we evaluate. We adjust based on what we learn. And this is helping us move through these really unpredictable times, especially during COVID. When COVID hit for us, we saw the thinking that we had been investing in since 2015. People were using that thinking as they were maneuvering all these new obstacles that this pandemic brought to us.",
